1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 O-O 5.d4 c6 6.Nc3 d5 7.Qb3 Qb6 {®b3 variation.
From our analysis above in Wojtkiewicz-Krasenkow, however, it appears that Black
is still struggling to equalize here. 'White’s straightforward plan of Wb3,
a2-a4, .if4, tDe5, and so on puts the second player under heavypositional
pressure. Meanwhile, when Black deviates from our stem game, White can find
other ways of challenging Black for control of e4. We’ve noted tDh4 and tDg5 as
being two of them. Overall, it appears that Black cannot count on getting too
pleasant a position with} 8.O-O Na6 {tDa6 first and only then playing for
....tfS. In this section, we will deal with these alternatives. First, what
other plans might Black have? One idea is to tryfor ...b7-b5 and ....ie6,
expanding on the queenside. This isn’t usually a first-rate option for Black
because, as we’ll see, it usually does more damage to his queenside than it is
worth in terms of counterplay. "White can focus on control of the c5 and e5
squares; these are good places for him to put his knights. His queen, after
moving to b3 or d3, generally rests nicely on c2, where it exerts pressure on
the c6-pawn and supports a possible e2-e4 pawn push in the center. White also
commonly plays a2-a3, either preventing Black’s ...b5-b4 push, or — if Black has
already played that — breaking up Black’s queenside formation. In the end,
Black’s a- and c-pawns are almost always weak. A second idea is for Black to
play something like ...tDbd7 and aim for the ...c6-c5 push. The reasoning for
Black here is that if he can pull this off without falling behind in
development, ^bite’s d4-pawn will be successfully challenged. Unfortunately for
the second player, this rarelyhappens. By the time Black achieves ...c6-c5,
White is usually far enough ahead in development that he can play dxc5 and
l'l:ac1, taking advantage of the open c-file. His bishops, often on the g2 and
e3 squares, rain down on Black’s a7- and b7-pawns. The white queen — which has
often been chased to b3 by this point, for instance by some knight maneuver
ending in ...tDb6 — can go to a3, putting further pressure on the c5-pa^. These
concepts may seem abstract at the moment, but after playing through the
variations given in the notes to this first game, they will be much easier to
visualize and comprehend. A word to the wise: in what follows, the reader should
pay special attention to the maneuvers of ^bite’s queen. When Black chases it,
where does it go? Back to c2 via a4, d3, or b3? To the a3 square to put pressure
on Black’s e7-pawn and to counter the idea of ...c6-c5? Developing a feel for
where best to place White’s queen is key to playing this system well for White.
We will begin with a game featuring several good queen moves from the first
