1.Nf3 Nf6 {tDfJ tDf6} 2.c4 e6 3.g3 b6 4.Bg2 Bb7 5.O-O Be7 {d4 right away} 6.Nc3
O-O 7.Re1 d5 {gel is rare enough fo catch many amateur players off-guard, but
strong enough to be played at the highest levels. Most of the resulting
positions are easy to play with White and fit well with other parts of Wojo’s
repertoire; for instance, there are numerous isolated queen’s pawn and “hanging
pawn” middlegames. White does not need an in-depth knowledge of the theory here
to use this opening effectively — just a strong command of the thematic ideas
behind the system, such as how to put pressure on Black’s queenside and in the
center, and so on. The Hedgehog The Hedgehog is a frequent guest at almost all
levels of chess play above 1800 or so. Black plays for the hedgehog pawn
formation (pawns on a6, b6, d6, e6, f7, g7, and h7) and hopes for dynamic play.
His pieces are often ideally placed to give him “spring-coiled” energy, ready to
be unleashed after any number of pawn breaks: ...b6-b5, ...d6-d5, and ...e6-e5
are all common possibilities. White, for his part, must try to make something
ofhis space advantage. He can advance on the queenside with b3-b4; play in the
center with e4-e5; or advance on the kingside, usually with g3-g4-g5. "White
should vary his strategy according to the specifics of what Black is doing. We
will first give the “Wojo Weapon” against Black’s hedgehog setup: the move 10
..tg5!?, a proven point-earner for White. Black seems to be okay if he knows
what he’s doing, but this rarely happened in Wojo’s experience. Then, we will
take a brief look at one of our own ideas for combatting the hedgehog} 8.cxd5
exd5 {d5, unlike in the notes to the previous game. Then} 9.d4 c6 {This is
considered Black’s best. Otherwise, "White will simply begin to mount pressure
in the center and on the queenside as he did in the previous game. Black must be
aggressive in order to avoid a similar fate. 1l...ttJxc5, transposing into the
note to Black’s move 7, is possible as well. When Black chooses to retake with
the pawn, a “hanging pawns” structure is reached. One key to White’s strategy
here is his pressure along the hl-a8 diagonal. Heoften is able to play something
like ttJf3-e5-c4 due to the pin on Black’s d-pawn} 10.Ne5 Nfd7 {ttJbd7is
certainly playable and has been ventured with Black by some strong grandmasters,
though} 11.Nd3 Bf6 {White’s knight on d3 clearly dominates its counterpart on
d7. It is easy to tell that Black’s last move was a failure from the standpoint
of completing his development: Rybka even recommends going backwith} 12.Nf4 Na6
{tLle5 also scores well} 13.e4 dxe4 {Black wants White to initiate the queen
trade. The downside to this is that his newly created b-pawn will be weak}
14.Nxe4 Be7 {White executes the thematic maneuver and highlights the weakness of
Black’s b6-pawn} 15.d5 cxd5 {.dxc416..ixb7 §a717.i.g2 would leave White with a
clear advantage thanks to his sweeping bishop pair} 16.Nxd5 Bxd5 {Sed1 first to
stop ...tLlc2 looks best. Then} 17.Qxd5 Nb4 {Sf8! threatens ...tLleS, when Black
at least has some tactical ideas to keep the game interesting. After lS.Sacl
tLleS} 18.Qb5 Rc8 {What else?} 19.Rd1 Qc7 {Sdl White exploits the open lines in
the center. Black’s piece coordination is so bad here that he is practically
losing} 20.Bf4 Ne5 {White decides that the safer} 21.a3 Nbc6 {®xa7 §fd8 22J'!b1
would have been good for White)} 22.Rac1 Kh8 {Yet another mistake involving the
move ...ge8. Instead, 22 ...ge5, holding on to the c5-pawn, may have possibly
saved Black} 1-0

