the game was agreed drawn according to ChessBase. Perhaps the rest of the moves
have simply been lost. White is clearly better after 30. Wd4!, retaking control
of the dark squares and tying Black’s rook on fS to the defense ofher f6-knight:
Black’s position now collapses, since 30 ... h6 or some other mundane movejust
loses to 31. Sf1, continuing to pile up on the f6-knight and forcing it to
desert the e4-pawn; and the two most tempting movesforBlackare both bad: 30 „
Ji:aS? loses to 31. jxb7,while 30 ... e3!? 31. Sd3 i.xg2 32. Sxe3 leaves Black
down a pawn after 32 ....!e4 33. ttJxe4 ttJxe4 34. Sxe4 35f V!e7 36. fufS+ V!xfS
37. V!e5. Black would simply have been left trying to suffer her way to a draw.
Summary: Black really went wrong out of the opening with her move 1O...ttJe4?!.
This wasted time andjust left White with a tremendous space advantage, which he
continued topress until the game was (unfortunately) agreed drawn. Had it not
been for this mistake, however, Black would probably have beenfine. iWhitefur
his part, might have been more successful with something other than
theprovoc-ative 9. V!b3!?. After 9. 0-0 and so on, ^White is better. Finally,
going back a littlefurther, 8... ttJbd7is definitely an improvementfor Black
over 8... Wfe8. In this case, we believe ^White gets an advantage, but there
isstill likely some theory to be worked out here. Thus 7... aS!? is worth
consideringfor Black. The next game considers 7... e5!? and 7... ttJe4!?.
