B.Zhak-K.Hansen, 2006, saw lS.e3 b5 19.. tfl b4 20.. tb5 h6 21. h3 g5 22. g4!
ttJe4 23. ttJxe4 fxe4 24hd7 exf3 25. ^b5 @g7 26. Wic2 with a noticeable
advantage for "White thanks to Black’s ugly bishop and weak pawn on f3. But most
of Black’s problems here were caused by ... h7-h6 and ... g7-g5, which weakened
his king. 9... ttJe4 10. he7 "White needs to playthis right away so as to
develop his queen’s knight to a3, preventing ... b7-b5 from Black. The recent
game V.Mikhalevski-M. Sadler, Oslo 2011, saw 1O.e3 a5 11. ttJel b5 12. i.xe7
Wixe7 13. c5 e5, when Black was already significantly better. Black has a space
advantage in the center and is doing well on the queenside. 10_Wixe7 11. ttJa3
b6 12. ttJc2 The “magic” ttJbl-a3-c2-el maneuver is now well underway. 12. „±b7
13. Wia3 Vlff7 Playable, but not best. GM Andy Soltis, in his book Pawn
Structure Chess, goes so far as to give this move a question mark. “Black’s
structure is geared for a kingside attack, but the endgame is preferable to the
passive middlegame he is now led into.” Thus we are left to conclude that 13..
:l1;![xa3 was Black’s best option. After 13... 'I1;!/xa3 14. 11Jxa3 aS, Black
can make "White sit down and scratch his head wondering where his advantage
went: forinstance 15. gacl gfd8 16. gfdl gac8 17. 11Jel .ia6 18. llJd3 g5 19. e3
20. f3 11Jef6 21. f <&e7 and it does not seem obvious at all that ^White has
anything: Black might even play ... c6-c5 himself in the near future. Also, ...
g5-g4 is a possibility. Furthermore, instead of Soltis’s suggestion of13
...'I1;!/xa3, what about the novelty 13... c5!? here? Then 14. cxd5 exd5 15.
dxc5 (15.11Jcel gfe8 16. 11Jd3 c4 17. 'I1;!/xe7 gxe7 18. llJde5 b5 19. 11Jxd7
gxd7 20. 11Je5 gc7 is unclear) 15... bxc5 16. b4 c4 17. gadl f4 18. llJfd4 (or
18. llJd2 llJd6) 18... gf6 is unclear. Black’s hanging pawns have been
blockaded, but Black does have ample activity. Most players of Black would
probably prefer 13... 'I1;!/xa3, but an attacking player like Shabalov or
someone playing Black in a must-win situation might do very well with this try.
In any case, it seems wrong to conclude that White has an advantage. 14. exd5
14. 11Jcel?! first runs into 14... dxc4 15. bxc4 c5, so "White plays this
capture first. Thiscapture is sometimes praised as being “thematic” because
"White now gains chances along the c-file. 14... cxd5?! It is this move that
looks like the real culprit to us. Black should keep the position unbalanced to
obtain counterplay. 14... exd5 15. 11Jcel f4!? (15... a5 16. 11Jd3 gac8 17. gacl
looks better for "White) 16. 11Jd3 (Rybka prefers 16.. 1h3 fxg3 17. fxg3!?, but
now 17... 'I1;!/e8 18. llJd3 gf6 19. 11Jfe5 llJxe5 20. 11Jxe5 i.c8 21.. 1g2 .ifS
looks fine for Black) 16... fxg3 17. hxg3 'I1;!/e8 with ... gf6 to follow would
leave Black with sufficient counterplay. 15. &eel a5 Soltis gives this move a
question mark. 15... 11Jc3 16. e3 gfc8 17. 11Jd3 'I1;!/f8 18:l1;![b2 gc7 was
perhaps a more stubborn way for Black to play. 16. &d3 Sfe8 17. &fe5 &xe5 18.
&xe5 ti'e8 19. 9fc1 ti'd8 20. e3 &e3 21 ..tfl At this point, White really does
have a slight edge. His bishop is better than Black’s, and he also has control
of e5 and many other dark squares. 22. b4?! A strange move. 22. Sc2 was better,
since 22 ... b5 with ... b5-b4 to follow was not an issue: 23. b4! ttJbl 24.
'I1Bb2 E:xc2 25. 1l;Yxc2 ttJa3 26. 'I1Bc5 axb4 27. 1l;Yxb4 leaves "White with
pressure against b5. 22... axb4 23. ti'b3 ^bite’s idea is to regain the pawn via
