ti'e6+ mfS 30. ttJxc4 ge7 30.. .dxc4 31. hc4 is of course hopeless for Black.
31. ti'f5+ gt7 32. 1l;Yxh71- 0 Summary: This game is sometimes used to
illustrate the power of White’s ka3 idea. But on closer scrutiny, does it really
seem like iWhite had any sort of guaranteed advantage here? Black had plenty
ofoptionsfor counterplay throughout the course of the game. On moves 13,14,23,
and 24, Black had better options that ranged from providing full counterplay to
leaving him only slightly worse. Of course, at this point, it is necessary to
backtrack and say that the plan of .ia3 is not at all a bad one for "White.
Several top players, including Kasparov, have played it. The system with .ia3 is
just often overrated and described as somehow “killing” the Stonewall — which,
in reality, it doesn’t. For instance, A.Huzman-V. Moskalenko, Lvov 1988, saw 1.
